   "title": "Apoxyomenos",
   "year": -330,
   "image": {
    "file": "File:Apoxyomenos Pio-Clementino Inv1185.jpg",
    "thumb640": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Apoxyomenos_Pio-Clementino_Inv1185.jpg/960px-Apoxyomenos_Pio-Clementino_Inv1185.jpg",
    "thumb1600": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4d/Apoxyomenos_Pio-Clementino_Inv1185.jpg",
    "pxW": 1500,
    "pxH": 3500
   },
   "cm": null,
   "collection": null,
   "story": {
    "extract": "Apoxyomenos is one of the conventional subjects of ancient Greek votive sculpture; it represents an athlete, caught in the familiar act of scraping sweat and dust from his body with the small curved instrument that the Greeks called a stlengis and the Romans a strigil.",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apoxyomenos"
   },
   "facts": [
    {
     "text": "A substantially complete bronze Apoxyomenos of this model, who scrapes his left hand with a strigil, held close to his thigh, was discovered by René Wouten from the northern Adriatic Sea between two islets, Vele Orjule and Kozjak, near Lošinj in Croatia, in 1996. René Wouten found the bronze statue fully covered in sponges and sea life.",
     "section": "Croatian Apoxyomenos",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apoxyomenos#Croatian_Apoxyomenos"
    }
   ],
   "license": {
    "name": "Public domain",
    "credit": "Copy after Lysippos"
   }
